Full worked example. Query has 5 CUIs. Topic has 6 CUIs.
Query CUIs (from "knee arthroplasty"):
  Q1: C5768203  Prosthetic arthroplasty of right knee   IC=14.8
  Q2: C0188146  Arthroplasty of knee, tibial plateau     IC=14.8
  Q3: C5688901  Arthroplasty using robotic assistance     IC=14.8
  Q4: C3873937  Knee femur prosthesis                     IC=14.8
  Q5: C5568443  Arthroplasty of knee planned              IC=14.8

Topic CUIs (case_2's knee surgery topic):
  T1: C5768203  Prosthetic arthroplasty of right knee   IC=14.8
  T2: C0845658  Total arthroplasty of knee, unilateral   IC=13.5
  T3: C0187960  Prosthetic arthroplasty of knee joint    IC=12.8
  T4: C0375841  Knee joint replacement                    IC=11.2
  T5: C0086511  Knee replacement arthroplasty              IC=10.5
  T6: C0581122  Persistent asthma (topic_cui)              IC=10.8
      (topic_cui is included in matchable set)

Signal 1: cui_ratio
Check each query CUI against all 6 topic CUIs. Try exact first, then parent-child, then MICA.
Q1 (C5768203) vs all topic CUIs:
  vs T1 (C5768203): EXACT MATCH → full credit = 1.0
  → done with Q1

Q2 (C0188146, Arthroplasty tibial plateau) vs all topic CUIs:
  vs T1: exact? NO
  vs T2: exact? NO
  vs T3: exact? NO
  vs T4: exact? NO
  vs T5: exact? NO
  vs T6: exact? NO
  → no exact match. try parent-child (walk 8 hops UP from each):

  Q2 ancestors: {Arthroplasty of knee (IC=9.7), Operation on knee (IC=6.4), ...}
  T2 ancestors: {Arthroplasty of knee (IC=9.7), Operation on knee (IC=6.4), ...}

  Q2 is child of "Arthroplasty of knee"
  T2 is child of "Arthroplasty of knee"
  They're siblings under the same parent, not parent-child of each other.

  T3 (C0187960, Prosthetic arthroplasty of knee joint):
  T3 is a PARENT of Q2 in UMLS hierarchy → parent-child match!
  
  credit = 1.0 × penalty
  penalty = IC(T3) / IC(Q2) = 12.8 / 14.8 = 0.865
  (parent is less specific → penalized)
  credit = 0.865
  → done with Q2

Q3 (C5688901, Robotic assistance) vs all topic CUIs:
  exact? NO for all
  parent-child? NO for all
  → try MICA:

  Q3 vs T1: walk UP from both, shared ancestors:
    MICA = Arthroplasty of knee (IC=9.7)
    Lin = 2 × 9.7 / (14.8 + 14.8) = 19.4 / 29.6 = 0.655

  Q3 vs T2: 
    MICA = Arthroplasty of knee (IC=9.7)
    Lin = 2 × 9.7 / (14.8 + 13.5) = 19.4 / 28.3 = 0.686  ← best

  Q3 vs T3:
    MICA = Arthroplasty of knee (IC=9.7)
    Lin = 2 × 9.7 / (14.8 + 12.8) = 19.4 / 27.6 = 0.703  ← even better

  Q3 vs T4:
    MICA = Operation on knee (IC=6.4)
    Lin = 2 × 6.4 / (14.8 + 11.2) = 12.8 / 26.0 = 0.492

  Q3 vs T5:
    MICA = Operation on knee (IC=6.4)
    Lin = 2 × 6.4 / (14.8 + 10.5) = 12.8 / 25.3 = 0.506

  Q3 vs T6:
    MICA = Procedure (IC=0.8)
    Lin = 2 × 0.8 / (14.8 + 10.8) = 1.6 / 25.6 = 0.063

  Best MICA: T3 with Lin=0.703
  credit = 0.703 (MICA match, weakest type)
  → done with Q3

Q4 (C3873937, Knee femur prosthesis [Device]) vs all topic CUIs:
  exact? NO
  parent-child? NO
  MICA:
    Q4 is a Device. Most topic CUIs are Procedures.
    Their shared ancestor is very high up: "Clinical procedure" (IC=2.1)
    Best MICA: T2 via "Knee procedure" (IC=5.5)
    Lin = 2 × 5.5 / (14.8 + 13.5) = 11.0 / 28.3 = 0.389
  credit = 0.389
  → done with Q4

Q5 (C5568443, Arthroplasty of knee planned) vs all topic CUIs:
  exact? NO
  parent-child? T4 (Knee joint replacement) is ancestor of Q5? 
    Walk UP from Q5... T4 is NOT a direct ancestor.
  parent-child? T5 (Knee replacement arthroplasty) is ancestor?
    Walk UP from Q5... YES, T5 is an ancestor at hop 2.
  credit = 1.0 × penalty = IC(T5)/IC(Q5) = 10.5/14.8 = 0.709
  → done with Q5
Now compute cui_ratio:
Q1: 1.000  (exact)
Q2: 0.865  (parent-child)
Q3: 0.703  (MICA)
Q4: 0.389  (MICA, weak — Device vs Procedure)
Q5: 0.709  (parent-child)

raw sum = 1.000 + 0.865 + 0.703 + 0.389 + 0.709 = 3.666
max possible = 5.0 (if all 5 were exact matches)

cui_ratio = 3.666 / 5.0 = 0.733

(simplified — real code also applies IC weighting and IDF,
but this shows the logic)

Signal 2: vec_sim
Ignores all the above. One dot product.
query centroid:  mean of Q1-Q5 embeddings, L2-normalized → [0.12, -0.05, 0.31, ...]
topic centroid:  mean of T1-T6 embeddings, L2-normalized → [0.11, -0.04, 0.29, ...]

vec_sim = dot product = 0.85

done.

Signal 3: lin_avg
Only for query CUIs that got NO match in cui_ratio. But in this example, all 5 got some match (exact, parent-child, or MICA). So:
Q1: matched (exact)        → skip
Q2: matched (parent-child) → skip
Q3: matched (MICA)         → skip
Q4: matched (MICA)         → skip
Q5: matched (parent-child) → skip

all matched → lin_avg uses the MICA scores from cui_ratio:
Q3 best Lin: 0.703
Q4 best Lin: 0.389

lin_avg = average of all Lin scores computed = (0.703 + 0.389) / 2 = 0.546
If Q4 had found NO MICA at all (zero shared ancestors within 8 hops):
Q4: no match anywhere → Lin = 0.0

lin_avg = (0.703 + 0.0) / 2 = 0.352
(worse — one query CUI has zero relationship to the topic)

Three signals together → Pass 3
           cui_ratio    vec_sim    lin_avg
case_2       0.733       0.85       0.546
group_71     0.050       0.12       0.190
group_44     0.000       0.10       0.080

z-score each column → sum per row → normalize to [0,1] → Pass 4 threshold

What each signal caught
Q1 → cui_ratio found it  (exact CUI match)
Q2 → cui_ratio found it  (parent-child, 8-hop walk)
Q3 → cui_ratio found it  (MICA sibling, 8-hop walk)
Q4 → cui_ratio found it  (weak MICA, different semantic type)
Q5 → cui_ratio found it  (parent-child, 8-hop walk)

vec_sim → confirmed they're related (centroids aligned)

lin_avg → measured HOW related the MICA matches are
          Q3 MICA Lin=0.703 (specific shared ancestor — strong)
          Q4 MICA Lin=0.389 (broad shared ancestor — weak)
All three agree: case_2 is a strong match. The combined score reflects that. Opus 4.6Extended
